etween the two measurements can cause the delta to be negative (handled by `Math.max(0, ...)`), but it can also be misleadingly large if other code allocates memory concurrently. This is acknowledged as a known limitation -- just flagging it for awareness.\n\n### 13. `flattenDependencies` would infinite-loop on cycles if not for the `deps.has()` guard\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 79-96\n\nThe `deps.has(depName)` check on line 87 happens to prevent infinite recursion on cycles, but this is an incidental side-effect rather than explicit cycle protection. Adding a comment clarifying that this guard implicitly breaks cycles would improve maintainability.\n\n### 14. No SQL injection risk, but consider parameterized table/column names\n\nThe prepared statements in `/workspace/src/reviews/index.ts` properly use parameterized queries (`@pluginName`, `?`), so there is no SQL injection risk for values. This is well done.\n\n### 15. `installPlugin` does not check for execution failure before returning\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/index.ts`, lines 77-82\n\nWhen the sandbox execution fails (e.g., the entry point throws), `installPlugin` still returns a successful `InstallResult` with `executionResult.success === false`. The plugin remains registered despite its entry point failing. Depending on the intended semantics, a failed entry point execution might warrant rolling back the registration.\n\n### 16. `deps` module uses `this` in an object literal, which is fragile\n\n**File:** `/workspace/src/deps/index.ts`, lines 19 and 99\n\n```typescript\nnode.dependencies.push(this.buildTree(depName, registry));\n// ...\nreturn this.detectCycles(name, registry) !== null;\n```\n\nThe `this` keyword in object literal methods works correctly when called as `depsService.buildTree(...)`, but would break if the methods are destructured: `const { buildTree } = createDepsService();`. This is a common JavaScript footgun. The other modules (registry, resolver, runner, reviews)